		<td class="statement">I design and develop interactions and technologies that embrace digital and physical experiences. 
		I am specifically interested in tools, techniques and devices that enable new interaction concepts for the augmentation and empowerment of human abilities. This includes 3D user interfaces, interaction techniques, augmented reality, mixed reality, virtual reality, ubiquitous computing, mobile devices, novel interfaces for medical imaging, multimodal systems, touch-screen interaction, and software/hardware prototyping.
		<br><br>
		The research projects are from exciting times and inspiring collaborations at different research labs and institutions, including <a target="_blank" href="http://www.media.mit.edu/">MIT</a>, <a target="_blank" href="http://www.cs.columbia.edu/graphics/home/">Columbia University</a>, <a target="_blank" href="http://ilab.cs.ucsb.edu/">University of California</a>, <a target="_blank" href="http://kth.se/csc">KTH (Royal Institute of Technology)</a>, and <a href="http://research.microsoft.com/en-us/groups/adapt/" target="_blank">Microsoft Research</a>. I have taught at Stanford University, Rhode Island School of Design and KTH. <br><br>

								<td>
									<table cellspacing="10" cellpadding="0"><tr><td class="pitch">	E-Textile Microinteractions leverage the I/O Braid architecture for soft electronics to combine continuous twist sensing with casual, discrete gestures, such as flicks, slides, pinches, grabs and pats.<br><br>I/O Braid is an interactive textile cord with embedded sensing and visuals. It senses user's proximity, touch, and twist, while embedded fiber optics enable spiraling light feedback.</td></tr></table>
